                translation: "What's still calm is easy to hold; what hasn't yet appeared is easy to plan for; what's brittle breaks easily; what's small scatters easily. Handle things before they exist; put things in order before disorder begins. A tree that fills your arms grew from a tiny sprout; a nine-story tower rose from a small mound of earth; a thousand-mile journey starts with a single step. Whoever forces an outcome ruins it; whoever grips too tightly loses it. People often ruin their efforts right at the edge of success. Stay as careful at the end as at the beginning, and nothing gets ruined. So the sage desires what others don't desire, values what's overlooked, and helps all things return to their own nature, without daring to force it.",
                theme: "wuwei",
                keyTakeaway: "Most failures happen right before the finish line, from carelessness born of overconfidence. Stay as attentive at the end as at the start.",
                article: "Chapter 64 opens with one of the text's most frequently quoted formulas: a journey of a thousand miles begins with a single step. The line's familiarity can obscure how much work it's doing in context, it's introduced specifically to argue that the same principle of small beginnings applies to holding onto stability just as much as it applies to starting something new: what is at rest is easy to hold, what has not yet emerged is easy to plan for; what is brittle is easy to shatter, what is small is easy to scatter. Act before it happens; put things in order before there is confusion.\n\nThis reframes prevention as fundamentally easier than correction, a claim that seems obvious in the abstract but is routinely ignored in practice, because early-stage problems don't feel urgent enough to justify the attention prevention requires, while late-stage problems, by the time they finally command attention, have already become far harder to resolve than they would have been earlier.\n\n\"People usually fail when they are about to succeed. Stay as careful at the end as at the beginning, and you will not fail\" names a specific and very common failure pattern, relaxing vigilance right at the point of near-completion, when the temptation to coast is strongest precisely because success finally feels assured. The chapter treats this relaxed vigilance as the actual cause of many failures that get retroactively blamed on bad luck or unforeseen circumstance.\n\nThe chapter's closing description of the sage, desiring what others don't desire, not prizing goods that are hard to obtain; learning what others don't learn, returning to what the masses have passed by; helping all things find their own nature, without daring to interfere, ties the whole chapter together: sustainable achievement comes from unglamorous, careful attention sustained evenly across an entire process, not from the more visible, more celebrated bursts of effort that tend to concentrate at the beginning and then quietly disappear well before the end."
