                article: "Chapter 65 opens with a claim that reads as counterintuitive, even mildly alarming, out of context: in ancient times, the best rulers didn't try to enlighten people, but tried to keep them simple, because people become hard to govern when they have too much cleverness. Read as advocacy for deliberate ignorance, this would clash badly with the rest of the text. Read more carefully, the chapter is targeting a specific kind of cleverness, calculating, self-interested cunning, \"too much cleverness\" as strategic manipulation, not knowledge or wisdom broadly.\n\n\"Governing a state with cunning robs the state; governing a state without cunning is a blessing to the state\" makes this distinction explicit. The concern isn't that people know too much, it's that a culture organized around clever maneuvering, everyone trying to outsmart everyone else, degrades trust and cooperation across the board. A community where people deal with each other straightforwardly functions better than one where everyone assumes everyone else is running an angle, regardless of how individually clever any given angle might be.\n\nThis applies cleanly to organizational culture. A workplace where people are constantly managing impressions, positioning politically, and calculating personal advantage, however individually rational each move might be, tends to be a worse place to work and a worse place to get things done than one built on more straightforward dealing, even if the straightforward culture looks, on paper, less sophisticated.\n\nThe chapter's closing move introduces the phrase \"mysterious virtue,\" describing a depth and breadth of character that seems to work in the opposite direction from ordinary things, yet ultimately leads to great harmony. This mysterious virtue is the alternative to the cunning being warned against, a way of engaging with people and situations that doesn't rely on outmaneuvering anyone, and that produces, over time, a more durable and harmonious outcome than cleverness ever quite manages on its own."
