                article: "Chapter 70 opens with a note of genuine frustration, unusual for the text's usually patient tone: my words are very easy to understand and very easy to practice, yet no one in the world can understand them or practice them. This isn't a claim of deliberate obscurity, the Tao Te Ching isn't arguing that its wisdom is intentionally hidden, it's expressing real puzzlement that something this accessible remains so widely unpracticed.\n\n\"Words have an ancestor; deeds have a master. Because people don't understand this, they don't understand me\" offers a partial explanation, that Laozi's teaching has a coherent underlying source, an \"ancestor,\" that ties everything together, but that most listeners engage with individual sayings in isolation rather than tracing them back to that shared root. Without seeing the underlying unity, the teaching can seem like scattered, disconnected advice rather than a coherent way of living.\n\n\"Those who understand me are few, and so I am to be valued\" is less boastful than it first sounds, it's closer to an honest acknowledgment that genuinely internalizing this philosophy, not just agreeing with individual lines but actually living differently because of them, is rare, and that rarity is precisely what gives the understanding its value, not despite being uncommon but because uncommon understanding tends to be harder-won and more deeply integrated.\n\nThe chapter's final image, the sage wears coarse clothes but carries jade within, captures something important about how this whole philosophy is meant to be held. The value described isn't meant to be worn on the surface for others to recognize and admire, it's meant to be carried quietly, internally, visible mainly in how someone actually moves through difficulty, not in any outward display designed to prove that the wisdom has been acquired."
