                article: "Chapter 75 draws a direct line between material extraction and social breakdown: people go hungry because those above them consume too much in taxes, that's why they go hungry. It's a blunt causal claim, poverty and hunger aren't treated here as inevitable or natural conditions, but as the direct downstream effect of excessive extraction by those with power over resources.\n\n\"People are hard to govern because those above them interfere too much, that's why they're hard to govern\" extends the same logic from material extraction to control more broadly. Difficulty in governing, in this framing, isn't primarily a character flaw in the governed, it's frequently a response, sometimes conscious, sometimes not, to being over-managed and over-restricted by those in charge. This reframes what might look like defiance or unruliness as often being the predictable consequence of excessive interference rather than a starting condition that interference is merely responding to.\n\n\"People take death lightly because those above them pursue life too intensely, that's why they take death lightly\" is the chapter's most severe claim, suggesting that a leadership class visibly and excessively absorbed in its own comfort and self-preservation can, by contrast, cheapen how the governed regard their own lives and safety, a kind of demoralization that follows from witnessing a stark and unaddressed gap between the ruling class's evident priorities and everyone else's actual circumstances.\n\nThe chapter's closing observation, that only those who don't make a big display of living are better than those who prize life too much, closes the loop, restraint and modesty at the top, not just as personal virtues but as a structural necessity, are what prevent the cascade of hunger, ungovernability, and demoralization the chapter has just described from taking hold in the first place."
